About the same time a strong south wind, ac- companied with continual thunder, drove such a sorce of water from the sea into the river Plata, that early in the morning the ship was extri- cated from that abyss of sands, and floated once again. Carried by the same wind, now favour- able to uS, we entered the port of Colonia, in, safety, next day about noon. After remaining there for two days, and being much tossed about, we were removed to the city of Buenos- Ayres. In crossing this river, which is about fifteen leagues wide, many of us endured more apprehension, and felt more sickness, than in the whole ocean. For want of a better, we went in a skiff, which age had rendered rotten, worm-eaten, and ruinous. Scarcely did one part adhere to the other. The fury of the raging wind increased our sear and our danger, for as it blew against us, our sails were too much bent, and one whole side of the skiff lay under water. But all this was nothing.
